The team also checked the responses of seal mothers by recording the number of times she raises her head off the ground and looks in the direction of her pups to check their well-being, during a specific time period.

Lead author, Dr Sean Twiss, of the School of Biological and Biomedical Sciences at Durham University, said: 'Our findings show that there is no such thing as an average seal.

'Individuals behave differently and do so consistently.

'We found that some seal mothers are very watchful when something potentially threatening approaches them, while other mums barely check their pups at all.

